<p>
    <pre>
        Linux looks for commands in its PATH.  You can see the value of your PATH with this in a terminal:

        <b>echo $PATH</b>

        You can change PATH with

        <b>PATH=/whatever/Your/New/Path:/or/:PathsAre</b>

        You can add to your current PATH with

        <b>PATH=$PATH:/your/additions</b>

        or

        <b>PATH=/your/additions/:$PATH</b>

        and then

        <b>EXPORT PATH</b>

        The first adds to the end of the current path and the latter puts before the current path.
        Linux searches the path from the beginning til it finds the command or exhausts the path.

        If we already have a java, javac or other command in our PATH and we want to replace with a different, then we want to put our additions at the beginning of the PATH.

        We can also personalize our PATH in <u>$HOME/.bash_profile</u>

        If we use a command like

        <b>which java</b>

        Linux will search our PATH until it finds it and will return the path to the command or it will tell us the command is not in our PATH
    </pre>
